  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n\n4. Transaction monitoring\n- Tracking unusual financial activities\n- Investigating potentially suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n5. Employee training\n- Educating staff about money laundering risks\n- Teaching identification of potential warning signs\n- Ensuring compliance with legal standards\n\n6. Risk assessment\n- Evaluating potential money laundering vulnerabilities\n- Developing strategies to mitigate risks\n- Updating compliance procedures\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, financial sanctions, and potential criminal investigations.",
